net.opentsdb.query.expression

Interface ITimeSyncedIterator

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    ExpressionIterator, IntersectionIterator, TimeSyncedIterator, UnionIterator

    public interface ITimeSyncedIterator
    An interface for expressions or queries that operate across time series and require point-by-point timestamp synchronization.
    Since:
    2.3

    • Method Detail

      • hasNext

        boolean hasNext()
        Returns:
        true if any of the series in the set has another value

      • next

        ExpressionDataPoint[] next(long timestamp)
        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp to fastforward to
        Returns:
        The data point array for the given timestamp. Implementations may throw an exception if the timestamp is invliad or they may return an empty array.

      • hasNext

        boolean hasNext(int index)
        Determines whether the individual series in the values array has another value. This may be used for non-synchronous iteration.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the series in the values array to check for
        Returns:
        True if the series has another value, false if not

      • next

        void next(int index)
        Fetches the next value for an individual series in the values array.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the series in the values array to advance

      • nextTimestamp

        Returns:

      • nullIterator

        void nullIterator(int index)
        Parameters:

      • getQueryTagKs

        ByteSet getQueryTagKs()
        Returns:
        a set of unique tag key UIDs from the filter list. If no filters were defined then the set may be empty.

      • setFillPolicy

        void setFillPolicy(NumericFillPolicy policy)
        Parameters:
        policy - A fill policy for the iterator. Iterators should implement a default

      • getFillPolicy

        NumericFillPolicy getFillPolicy()
        Returns:
        the fill policy for the iterator

      • getCopy

        ITimeSyncedIterator getCopy()
        Returns:
        a copy of the iterator. This should return references to underlying data objects but not necessarily copy all of the underlying data (to avoid memory explosions). This is useful for creating other iterators that operate over the same data.
